As promised, i will continue to rehash the process that has led me to where i am now in my artistic journey and to the re-manifestation of my imaginary friend Pi, now Pi137 ✨✊😭
.
This was my 2nd black color drawing in a series that explored folds of space and light deeply. I used the same shirt that i came to adore from my previous drawing "It All Depends", and pushed it to explode in an Asymmetric yet more abstracted manner. Although by this point i had become more in tune with detail from life so i was incorporporating the ribbed colars and the sewn seams as well as the folds. ps no finger smudging was ever thought of nor used lol, only circles made with a sharp pencil to achieve a smooth gradient. i despise smudging....sorry.
.
I digress, In this drawing "Growth",
i spent much of my time sculpting the shirt itself before drawing to achieve the most interesting clusters of forms. This is half a sculpture as it is a drawing. As a result, i can see and imagine so many different anamorphic and natural forms...in what was only a shirt to those around me. This drawing taught me that it is up to us to see the world we live in and transform it with our minds and hearts. .
If your life was a shirt, have fun in it, push your limits in it, look out for stains, clean it properly, fold and stash it accordingly for rest and repeat. dont leave it stagnant on the floor.
.
hand placed for size reference
enjoy the view
.

First time posting up some in-progress hotshots! I shot this with a Didymium lens filter, on my 50mm macro lens. I really cant believe how well the filter was able to remove the sodium flare.
If you have ever tried to shoot the flame its typically very hard and heres why. When the super oxygen rich flame starts to heat up the glass molecules, sodium in the glass itself is heated or burned. This burn creates a bright yellow light that makes it difficult to see and photograph The solution is didymium, which is a mixture of the two elements praseodymium and neodymium. Together these two work together to block yellowish light around 589nm. It was discovered as eye protection by Sir William Crookes around 1913. 
This is my homie @daljar_glass killing it making a pocket mib he gifted me #daljarglass #glassscience #didymiumlens #headyart #degenerateart #bmr5003
